795
01:23:31,670 --> 01:23:32,971
[SPEAKER_15]: Go ahead, Mr. Alexander.

796
01:23:33,111 --> 01:23:33,331
[SPEAKER_15]: OK.

797
01:23:33,411 --> 01:23:34,032
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Mr. Chair.

798
01:23:34,488 --> 01:23:42,078
[SPEAKER_15]: So I think it's probably not – it may be – I don't want to say the opposite, but it's slightly different.

799
01:23:42,278 --> 01:23:52,951
[SPEAKER_15]: And what I think is actually that D13, as was originally written, in today's reality is likely sort of duplicative or unnecessary.

800
01:24:02,068 --> 01:24:02,348
[SPEAKER_15]: team.

801
01:24:02,428 --> 01:24:24,247
[SPEAKER_15]: So the new code that was adopted in the beginning of this year and will be implemented at the beginning of next year, I want to say for all intents and purposes already requires this, already requires electric utilities for residential heat and hot water.

802
01:24:25,341 --> 01:24:45,259
[SPEAKER_15]: So the combination of that plus the fact that the project will be going through a MEPA environmental review, which has, in my experience and our experience, a very detailed review from the Department of Energy resources, it will also be

803
01:24:46,783 --> 01:24:54,447
[SPEAKER_15]: You know, again, I don't want to say it's 100%, but it's probably pretty close to 100% certainty that this project will already be electric, heat, and hot water.

804
01:24:54,607 --> 01:25:14,659
[SPEAKER_15]: So I don't know if Cliff or Andrew have other thoughts on that, but that, you know, I don't think we need to go around, you know, too detailed in terms of how this language is written or if it's included at all, quite frankly, given the other facts, both in building code and in the state environmental review that we're going to undertake.

805
01:25:16,838 --> 01:25:17,679
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, thank you.

806
01:25:18,200 --> 01:25:23,204
[SPEAKER_03]: I just want to check in with Director Hunt first and then we can go to Mr. Brommer and Mr. Stephan.

807
01:25:23,625 --> 01:25:31,913
[SPEAKER_10]: I was just going to add that it's fairly standard to include fossil fuels for emergency generators simply because

808
01:25:32,595 --> 01:25:34,896
[SPEAKER_10]: they're used when electricity is out.

809
01:25:35,596 --> 01:25:40,677
[SPEAKER_10]: And so the idea being that you have some other way of providing power.

810
01:25:40,737 --> 01:25:45,458
[SPEAKER_10]: So usually it would be onsite diesel, natural gas.

811
01:25:45,918 --> 01:25:55,040
[SPEAKER_10]: It's funny, natural gas is actually more reliable in an extreme emergency, but usually diesel or oil is what one would expect for an emergency generator.

812
01:25:56,028 --> 01:26:00,450
[SPEAKER_10]: I just thought I'd share that, that it's not a cop-out, it's actually you need that.

813
01:26:00,931 --> 01:26:09,155
[SPEAKER_10]: The alternative is solar with battery storage, which is, I've been trying to get that done for six years in Medford, it's really hard.

814
01:26:10,936 --> 01:26:21,802
[SPEAKER_03]: Understood, yeah, so the question wasn't so much about the exception for emergency generation, it was the switching from shall language to something a little bit more flexible.

815
01:26:22,863 --> 01:26:23,383
[SPEAKER_10]: Oh, okay.

816
01:26:24,901 --> 01:26:28,843
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, Mr. Boehmer, do you have anything you'd like to say on this matter?

817
01:26:29,524 --> 01:26:52,877
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, and I'd appreciate Andrew weighing in as well, but I think even if Medford did do the opt-in code, which is some more of the really juiced up version of the new code, I don't think that would actually necessarily require going all electric.

818
01:26:54,689 --> 01:27:14,203
[SPEAKER_04]: My understanding of that code is that the thrust of it is really more on efficiency, air sealing, which is why the opt-in requires at least a passive house pre-certification process.

819
01:27:14,523 --> 01:27:22,129
[SPEAKER_04]: I think you actually can, even under the new code, still use at least natural gas.

820
01:27:23,647 --> 01:27:41,173
[SPEAKER_04]: So the reason that I was suggesting and others do is it's really just the way the world is going now and many communities in Massachusetts are already requiring the all electric with the exception of backup power.

821
01:27:43,233 --> 01:27:43,653
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

822
01:27:44,053 --> 01:27:45,594
[SPEAKER_03]: Mr. Stebbins, anything you'd like to add?

823
01:27:47,194 --> 01:27:48,415
[SPEAKER_02]: No, I agree with Mr. Bowmer.

824
01:27:51,109 --> 01:28:07,157
[SPEAKER_02]: The way the code is to be set up is that there's actually a penalty if you use fossil fuels, your HRS rating, which is a rating of, it's sort of a calculated rating of your performance per unit.

825
01:28:08,817 --> 01:28:18,102
[SPEAKER_02]: If you utilize gas in a project, you need to provide a more efficient building than if you're providing all electric and that's,

826
01:28:19,388 --> 01:28:24,029
[SPEAKER_02]: set up to sort of encourage conversion to all electric.

827
01:28:24,429 --> 01:28:39,093
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's my understanding of the current low-rise residential code and the upcoming, shortly here, the multi-rise code.

828
01:28:39,133 --> 01:28:43,914
[SPEAKER_02]: So not a complete exclusion, so.

829
01:28:46,414 --> 01:28:46,774
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

830
01:28:46,794 --> 01:28:48,855
[SPEAKER_03]: And I saw Commissioner Forty raised his hand.

831
01:28:49,537 --> 01:29:01,648
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I was just going to echo the both of the previous two gentlemen that, yes, they incentivize a higher rating, which is a worse energy code rating for using fossil fuels.

832
01:29:01,728 --> 01:29:13,560
[SPEAKER_01]: So so I mean, for using electric, they allow a higher rating for electric appliances because you're actually you're actually going more green, the more green direction.

833
01:29:14,410 --> 01:29:25,456
[SPEAKER_01]: when you use fossil fuels, your HRS rating requirement goes way down, which is more energy efficient and more tighter air sealing and all of the other R factor requirements tend to increase.

834
01:29:25,516 --> 01:29:26,877
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's kind of the way it is.

835
01:29:26,937 --> 01:29:30,178
[SPEAKER_01]: So the code will kind of dictate what this building is gonna look like.

836
01:29:30,819 --> 01:29:34,601
[SPEAKER_01]: And I got a feeling that it's going all electric.

837
01:29:34,641 --> 01:29:41,705
[SPEAKER_01]: I think by the time this permit rolls around, I think we're gonna be well into the new energy code and possibly into our specialized stretch energy code.

838
01:29:41,725 --> 01:29:42,405
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's it.

839
01:29:43,512 --> 01:29:44,653
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, thank you.

840
