1166
02:08:25,289 --> 02:08:27,370
[SPEAKER_14]: This proposal totals about 750, which would leave about 250, 260,000

1167
02:08:31,960 --> 02:08:35,063
[SPEAKER_14]: dollars worth of linkage payments still being made to the city.

1168
02:08:35,503 --> 02:08:36,664
[SPEAKER_14]: So I did want to make that point.

1169
02:08:38,105 --> 02:08:52,617
[SPEAKER_14]: The other point I wanted to make about I&I is the linkage payment obligations pre-exist the I&I removal obligation.

1170
02:08:53,017 --> 02:09:00,083
[SPEAKER_14]: And so I think another way that we were thinking about the I&I work is it's really double counting work.

1171
02:09:01,720 --> 02:09:21,429
[SPEAKER_14]: a project that if the I&I requirement did not exist and a project was making a substantial payment for sewer work, the city could have that money to go out on its own and do I&I mitigation work, inflow and infiltration mitigation work in the city.

1172
02:09:22,850 --> 02:09:25,211
[SPEAKER_14]: Here, we're going to do that.

1173
02:09:25,991 --> 02:09:30,073
[SPEAKER_14]: By both having the applicant do that I&I work and

1174
02:09:31,630 --> 02:09:36,273
[SPEAKER_14]: potentially not give a credit for that work.

1175
02:09:37,693 --> 02:09:38,854
[SPEAKER_14]: It's a bit of double counting.

1176
02:09:40,535 --> 02:09:53,182
[SPEAKER_14]: The third comment I would make is that we've been talking a little bit about these items of work as falling within different buckets.

1177
02:09:54,522 --> 02:09:57,664
[SPEAKER_14]: And I'm not sure we need to necessarily think of them that way.

1178
02:09:58,635 --> 02:10:07,200
[SPEAKER_14]: if we think of a 40B waiver as being distinct from the credit system that exists under the zoning ordinance for an existing 40A project.

1179
02:10:08,140 --> 02:10:20,927
[SPEAKER_14]: And I don't think, and Tim kicked me under the virtual table if I'm wrong, but a dollar paid to the city by Mill Creek is a dollar paid to the city.

1180
02:10:21,488 --> 02:10:27,171
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't think Mill Creek cares whether that goes to a sewer fund or a park fund

1181
02:10:27,695 --> 02:10:28,495
[SPEAKER_14]: or a street fund.

1182
02:10:29,216 --> 02:10:40,860
[SPEAKER_14]: So that may be helpful to the board if they're inclined to consider these requests to separate the items of work from the different prescriptive buckets that are in the zoning ordinance.

1183
02:10:40,920 --> 02:10:50,403
[SPEAKER_14]: And it could just be a credit against the total payment or as to portions of the payment to help maintain the allocation of the payments being made.

1184
02:10:53,127 --> 02:10:54,529
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you, Mr. Renier.

1185
02:10:54,549 --> 02:11:00,814
[SPEAKER_03]: Just a clarifying question about the double counting element on the INI.

1186
02:11:00,894 --> 02:11:14,947
[SPEAKER_03]: So in the, all right, so let's suppose that the board waived linkage in its entirety or that linkage was never a part of the ordinance to begin with.

1187
02:11:16,468 --> 02:11:17,129
[SPEAKER_03]: So you presented,

1188
02:11:18,772 --> 02:11:27,636
[SPEAKER_03]: two scenarios, the scenario where you're doing the work and the scenario where the city's doing the work.

1189
02:11:28,916 --> 02:11:36,039
[SPEAKER_03]: Under the law, in the scenario where the city is doing the work, would you be paying the city to do that?

1190
02:11:36,339 --> 02:11:43,722
[SPEAKER_03]: Or would the city just do it of its own free will?

1191
02:11:46,562 --> 02:12:04,666
[SPEAKER_14]: Well, I think that in that instance, a project would pay the sewer linkage fee, and then the city would have that money to do I&I work if it wanted to do that work or not, if it had areas that it knew was problematic.

