[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, thank you, Mr. Chair.

1398
02:36:44,448 --> 02:36:46,909
[SPEAKER_15]: I agree with what Ms.

1399
02:36:46,929 --> 02:36:48,530
[SPEAKER_15]: Barrett and Chris are talking about.

1400
02:36:48,651 --> 02:36:49,491
[SPEAKER_15]: I think we're close.

1401
02:36:49,611 --> 02:36:52,233
[SPEAKER_15]: I think we've covered the ground tonight that we wanted to cover.

1402
02:36:52,753 --> 02:36:54,114
[SPEAKER_15]: The board does have what they need.

1403
02:36:54,194 --> 02:37:04,801
[SPEAKER_15]: If we could get a couple of these administrative items cleaned up while the hearing's still open here for the next few minutes, I think that's, you know, I don't think it's gonna take us an hour, for instance, to update

1404
02:37:05,879 --> 02:37:15,705
[SPEAKER_15]: Um, the waiver lists and get the retail uses incorporated and then forward along the, the list of conditions as drafted and revised live tonight.

1405
02:37:15,785 --> 02:37:20,388
[SPEAKER_15]: So if you can give us a couple of minutes, I think that's where we're headed, but I want to make sure I'm not missing anything.

1406
02:37:22,670 --> 02:37:26,412
[SPEAKER_03]: So I guess I just have a procedural question for, for Judy.

1407
02:37:26,512 --> 02:37:26,832
[SPEAKER_03]: So, um,

1408
02:37:29,629 --> 02:37:39,816
[SPEAKER_03]: can we close the hearing and have them send the last drafts same day or does the hearing technically need to stay open until the last?

1409
02:37:39,876 --> 02:37:42,638
[SPEAKER_08]: You should not take information after the hearing is closed.

1410
02:37:43,298 --> 02:37:43,518
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

1411
02:37:48,302 --> 02:37:49,062
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1412
02:37:49,663 --> 02:37:52,625
[SPEAKER_08]: Now that doesn't mean, I mean, does the board need to see?

1413
02:37:54,090 --> 02:38:05,532
[SPEAKER_08]: The edits that are left, or are you, given where you are with this, why can't we just work on this decision between me, the staff, Amy, and the applicant's attorney?

1414
02:38:10,273 --> 02:38:17,814
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, I'm wondering, so why don't, I'm certainly amenable to the recess, and I think that might be helpful for the applicant or attorney.

1415
02:38:18,715 --> 02:38:20,375
[SPEAKER_03]: Why don't we,

1416
02:38:22,498 --> 02:38:46,701
[SPEAKER_03]: Why don't you discuss and figure out if you're comfortable just shipping, even if it's not quite finished, whatever you have before we close the hearing tonight, and then just trust that the folks working on it are gonna take what we've already discussed tonight and correctly codify that in the draft order, Director Hunt.

1417
02:38:48,377 --> 02:39:03,982
[SPEAKER_10]: I was just going to suggest that maybe if the applicant wanted five minutes to talk it wouldn't be a bad idea for Judy and Mike and Dennis or and I are to get on the phone just quick and make sure we all understand

1418
02:39:05,022 --> 02:39:05,622
[SPEAKER_10]: the process.

1419
02:39:05,662 --> 02:39:19,307
[SPEAKER_10]: I think we've been, when we write decisions, having, you know, Dennis writes it, the chair reviews it, at least on the CD board side, often we have the applicant review it and make sure we're all, there's no conflict.

1420
02:39:19,387 --> 02:39:20,827
[SPEAKER_10]: It's not a debate at that time.

1421
02:39:20,907 --> 02:39:27,490
[SPEAKER_10]: It's a making sure that we've all understood, like we're reading the words the same way.

1422
02:39:27,510 --> 02:39:28,710
[SPEAKER_10]: I understand.

1423
02:39:29,070 --> 02:39:33,652
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, it's, the advice I'm giving you is don't,

1424
02:39:34,608 --> 02:39:37,529
[SPEAKER_08]: close the hearing and take documents after you've closed it.

1425
02:39:38,849 --> 02:39:45,191
[SPEAKER_08]: If there's a practice in place that there is some discussion with the applicant after the hearing is closed, that's up to you guys.

1426
02:39:45,852 --> 02:39:49,393
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm just giving you advice based on what I've seen.

1427
02:39:51,934 --> 02:40:01,056
[SPEAKER_06]: So for clarity for me, does that mean, Judy, so when Mike had put out an ask for the DEI,

1428
02:40:03,195 --> 02:40:07,698
[SPEAKER_06]: folks in the city to give input on, you know, like the mural, right?

1429
02:40:08,899 --> 02:40:10,961
[SPEAKER_06]: So does that mean that's shut down now, right?

1430
02:40:11,021 --> 02:40:14,283
[SPEAKER_06]: Because we're using what we have in this space because we're closing it down.

1431
02:40:14,344 --> 02:40:28,414
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, how, where is it that, because I think to some extent, for example, that one small piece of it, I think is somewhat important for us because, you know, we don't just want a square box of a building.

1432
02:40:28,474 --> 02:40:31,497
[SPEAKER_06]: Like we really wanted to add that character, like that was important, right?

1433
02:40:33,113 --> 02:40:37,854
[SPEAKER_06]: How would you direct us for that, for example?

1434
02:40:37,914 --> 02:40:51,458
[SPEAKER_08]: If the board's already agreed in principle to something, and all you're doing is asking another city board for input on wording, but the content has already been agreed to, I don't think that's a problem.

1435
02:40:53,240 --> 02:40:53,940
[SPEAKER_08]: Do you see what I mean?

1436
02:40:54,001 --> 02:41:03,007
[SPEAKER_08]: It's like, very typically what happens with these cases is when the board has all the information they need, they often have not even seen a complete draft of the decision.

1437
02:41:03,828 --> 02:41:10,772
[SPEAKER_08]: The critical piece, Chris, tell me if you disagree, but the critical piece is the conditions, because that's what the applicant's really gonna have to live with.

1438
02:41:11,153 --> 02:41:14,695
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, you can take their procedural history and curse them to death.

1439
02:41:14,735 --> 02:41:15,436
[SPEAKER_08]: It doesn't matter.

1440
02:41:15,756 --> 02:41:16,917
[SPEAKER_08]: Nobody appeals on that.

1441
02:41:16,977 --> 02:41:18,098
[SPEAKER_08]: They appeal on conditions.

1442
02:41:18,848 --> 02:41:28,494
[SPEAKER_08]: So if the conditions are agreed to, in principle, and what we're doing is managing the language, I don't think the board needs to keep the hearing open at all.

1443
02:41:28,614 --> 02:41:35,118
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm only concerned that if there's additional information that the board somehow needs, that the applicant's going to be coming forth with,

1444
02:41:35,718 --> 02:41:37,039
[SPEAKER_08]: then I wouldn't close the hearing.

1445
02:41:37,379 --> 02:41:46,425
[SPEAKER_08]: But if everybody's in agreement about what's going to happen, and it's a question of getting the language down and finishing the rest of the parts of the decision, I don't see why you need to keep the hearing open.

1446
02:41:46,485 --> 02:41:55,710
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm very accustomed to boards, once you've gotten to the point of a comfort level with the conditions, at least the content of them, saying, that's fine.

1447
02:41:55,770 --> 02:41:57,491
[SPEAKER_08]: Now, go draft the rest of the decision.

1448
02:41:57,531 --> 02:42:02,114
[SPEAKER_08]: The board has 40 days to deliberate once you close the hearing.

1449
02:42:03,742 --> 02:42:10,004
[SPEAKER_08]: You don't, the reason to keep the hearing open is if there's evidence you need that would affect your decision.

1450
02:42:11,384 --> 02:42:23,448
[SPEAKER_08]: If you have the information that you need to make your decision, there is no reason to keep the hearing open because you can deliberate, you can decide in deliberations to deny the application, but you have the information you need.

1451
02:42:23,468 --> 02:42:27,549
[SPEAKER_08]: That's the question.

1452
02:42:27,569 --> 02:42:29,910
[SPEAKER_03]: All right.

1453
02:42:30,970 --> 02:42:31,791
[SPEAKER_03]: Thanks, Mr. Barrett.

1454
02:42:32,632 --> 02:42:39,497
[SPEAKER_03]: Chair awaits a motion for a, why don't we make it a 10 minute recess?

1455
02:42:43,401 --> 02:42:43,961
[SPEAKER_03]: To 1035.

1456
02:42:46,303 --> 02:42:52,789
[SPEAKER_13]: A motion for a 10 minute recess to 1035 tonight.

1457
02:42:52,929 --> 02:42:54,130
[SPEAKER_13]: I'll second that.

1458
